<br />

To

free up space for discussing contemporary developments like digital filmmaking,

we&rsquo;ve

had to purge the introductory chapter that was published in the first two editions.

That chapter tried to introduce the aims of the book and to float some general

considerations about doing research into film history. Some of those concerns

were practical, such as the difference between primary and secondary sources

of information. Other concerns were more theoretical, such as the distinction

between methodological holism and methodological individualism.<br />

<br />

Nothing like

this introduction has ever appeared in any film textbook that we know, and we

are somewhat sad to drop it. Thanks to the Internets, however, nothing need be

lost. We are posting a revised version of the introduction, called &ldquo;<a href="/essays/doing.php"><strong>Doing

Film History</strong></a>,&rdquo; in the Essays wing of this website. It&rsquo;s

also available at the <a href="http://novella.mhhe.com/sites/0073386138/information_center_view0/" target="_blank"><strong>McGraw-Hill

website devoted to&nbsp;<em>Film History</em></strong></a>. That

site includes our bibliographies and our chapter-by-chapter Notes and Queries,

supplementary information and ideas about film history. Even if you&rsquo;re

not reading the book, you may find some of our brief, bloggish items of interest.

Just go to the <a href="http://novella.mhhe.com/sites/0073386138/student_view0/index.html" target="_blank">Student

Edition</a> information and click on any chapter&rsquo;s Notes and

Queries.</p>

